        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Second Fiddle to an Old Master''(Op-Ed, April 7), John Marchese does not mention the fear that many violinists have about buying a modern instrument: it may not age well.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Second Fiddle to an Old Master''(Op-Ed, April 7), John Marchese does not mention the fear that many violinists have about buying a modern instrument: it may not age well.</p>
        <p>When a new violin is played, it is ''broken in,'' and sometimes a modern broken-in violin does not sound as good as the day it was bought.</p>
        <p>With an old Stradivarius, we can be sure that the sound quality is stable and unlikely to change any time soon -- because it has already stood the test of time.</p>
        <p>Robert Ackerberg  Massapequa, N.Y., April 7, 2007</p>
      </block>
